{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17508998","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17508998"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:11:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:11:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11367"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11367","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11367"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.16,0.57,0.11,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4012"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78713"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4012","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4012"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11367"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64056"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"256"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"3406"},{"type":"tags","id":"3496"},{"type":"tags","id":"9084"},{"type":"tags","id":"9270"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4300"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4409"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27001"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78713","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78713"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 67-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a 10-day history of jaundice, itching, nausea, and vomiting. He complains of dark urine with normal frequency and volume, and foul-smelling, pale stools. He has had no weight change, no haematemesis, and no abdominal pain. He has a 40 pack-year smoking history and heavy alcohol use of at least six standard drinks a day. \u003Cbr /\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his blood pressure is 130/86 mmHg, pulse 90/min, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. His Glasgow Coma Score is 15, and his BMI is 26.5 kg/m\u00b2. His chest is clear, and heart sounds are dual with no murmur. His abdomen is distended, his gallbladder is palpable but there is no tenderness. A digital rectal examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Mirizzi syndrome","Alcoholic hepatitis","Tumour of the head of pancreas","Decompensated liver disease","Haemolysis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EJaundice and pruritus are consistent with hyperbilirubinaemia. Specifically, dark urine and pale stools are consistent with \u003Cem\u003Econjugated\u003C/em\u003E hyperbilirubinaemia, which occurs in obstructive jaundice. Conjugated bilirubin is water soluble and hence excreted in the urine making it dark, while the lack of stercobilinogen in the stool makes it pale. The foul-smelling steatorrhoea is suggestive of lipid in stools, which can be caused by exocrine pancreatic duct obstruction. \u003Cstrong\u003ETumours of the head of pancreas\u003C/strong\u003E usually present with obstructive jaundice and without pain. This patient has Courvoisier\u0027s sign (palpable enlarged gallbladder which is not tender in a jaundiced patient), which is specific but not sensitive for malignant bile duct obstruction. The abdominal distension could be due to malignant ascites.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMirizzi syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is the extrinsic compression of the common bile duct from calculi in the cystic duct or the gallbladder. It usually presents as episodic cholangitis, and sometimes with acute cholecystitis. It cannot be ruled out but it is less likely the diagnosis here given the absence of pain and fever, which are common findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlcoholic hepatitis\u003C/strong\u003E also presents abruptly with conjugated hyperbilirubinaemia. While jaundice is common, these patients usually also have tender hepatomegaly, fever, and tachycardia, making this less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecompensated liver failure\u003C/strong\u003E could manifest as any of the following:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHepatic encephalopathy - he is not confused\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPortal hypertension - no signs of ascites or distended veins\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHepatorenal syndrome - he has urine\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHepatopulmonary syndrome - his chest is clear\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis history is not suggestive of \u003Cstrong\u003Ehaemolysis\u003C/strong\u003E, and the hyperbilirubinaemia is not unconjugated (which is insoluble and thus not excreted in urine) - which would be the case in haemolysis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Painless obstructive jaundice must raise suspicion of a pancreatic head tumour.","Courvoisier\u0027s sign is indicative of malignant obstruction of the bile duct.","Conjugated hyperbilirubinaemia presents with dark urine and pale stools."],"references":["Beckingham IJ, Ryder SD. ABC of diseases of liver, pancreas, and biliary system. Investigation of liver and biliary disease. BMJ. 2001 Jan 6;322(7277):33-6. doi: 10.1136/bmj.322.7277.33. PMID: 11141153; PMCID: PMC1119305. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/11141153/","Freelove R, Walling AD. Pancreatic cancer: diagnosis and management. Am Fam Physician. 2006 Feb 1;73(3):485-92. PMID: 16477897. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16477897/","Singh S, Sawal A. Comprehensive Review on Pancreatic Head Cancer: Pathogenesis, Diagnosis, and Treatment Challenges in the Quest for Improved Survival. Cureus. 2024 Feb 16;16(2):e54290. doi: 10.7759/cureus.54290. PMID: 38500905; PMCID: PMC10945288. Avaialble from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10945288/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64056"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11367"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64056","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64056"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-12T14:42:10+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-12T14:42:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4012"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78713"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"dat